---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import NewsletterBlock from '../../components/NewsletterBlock.astro';
import {
  buildCollectionPageSchema,
  buildItemListSchema,
  buildFaqSchema,
  buildBreadcrumbSchema,
} from '../../lib/schema';

const collectionSchema = buildCollectionPageSchema({
  name: 'Family-Friendly Things to Do on the Mornington Peninsula',
  description: 'Kid-tested picks for families visiting the Mornington Peninsula — beaches, attractions, walks, cafés, and markets.',
  path: '/explore/family-friendly',
  dateModified: '2026-04-23',
});

const itemListSchema = buildItemListSchema({
  name: 'Family-Friendly Things to Do on the Mornington Peninsula',
  description: 'Kid-tested picks for families on the Mornington Peninsula.',
  listPath: '/explore/family-friendly',
  items: [
    { name: 'Arthurs Seat Eagle gondola', path: '/explore/arthurs-seat-lookout', itemType: 'TouristAttraction', addressLocality: 'Arthurs Seat' },
    { name: 'Balnarring Beach', path: '/explore/balnarring-beach', itemType: 'Beach', addressLocality: 'Balnarring' },
    { name: 'Safety Beach foreshore', path: '/explore/safety-beach-foreshore', itemType: 'Beach', addressLocality: 'Safety Beach' },
    { name: 'Mount Martha Beach', path: '/explore/mount-martha-beach', itemType: 'Beach', addressLocality: 'Mount Martha' },
    { name: 'Ashcombe Maze and Lavender Gardens', path: '/journal/ashcombe-maze-visitor-guide', itemType: 'TouristAttraction', addressLocality: 'Shoreham' },
    { name: 'Cape Schanck boardwalk', path: '/explore/cape-schanck-boardwalk', itemType: 'TouristAttraction', addressLocality: 'Cape Schanck' },
    { name: 'Mornington foreshore walk', path: '/explore/mornington-foreshore-walk', itemType: 'TouristAttraction', addressLocality: 'Mornington' },
    { name: 'Red Hill Community Market', path: '/explore/red-hill-market', itemType: 'TouristAttraction', addressLocality: 'Red Hill' },
  ],
});

const faqSchema = buildFaqSchema([
  {
    q: 'What is the best beach on the Mornington Peninsula for families with young children?',
    a: 'Balnarring Beach — shallow, calm, clear water, easy parking. Safety Beach is a close second.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is Peninsula Hot Springs suitable for children?',
    a: 'Peninsula Hot Springs has a children\'s bathing area, but the experience is primarily designed for adults. Ages 5+ can enjoy parts of it; under-5s are a judgment call.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the best paid attraction for families on the Mornington Peninsula?',
    a: 'Arthurs Seat Eagle gondola for children 2–12. Ashcombe Maze for children 5+.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the best season for a family Peninsula trip?',
    a: 'Summer for beaches. The school holidays (January, July) are crowded; October and early December have good weather with lower crowds.',
  },
]);

const breadcrumbSchema = buildBreadcrumbSchema([
  { name: 'Home', url: 'https://peninsulainsider.com.au/' },
  { name: 'Explore', url: 'https://peninsulainsider.com.au/explore/' },
  { name: 'Family Friendly' },
]);

const breadcrumbItems = [
  { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
  { label: 'Explore', href: '/explore' },
  { label: 'Family Friendly' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Family-Friendly Things to Do on the Mornington Peninsula · Peninsula Insider"
  description="Kid-tested picks for families visiting the Mornington Peninsula — the best beaches for young children, gondola, maze, walks, and markets."
  section="explore"
  canonical="https://peninsulainsider.com.au/explore/family-friendly/"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(collectionSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(itemListSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbItems} />

  <article class="article">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 class="article__title">Family-Friendly Things to Do on the Mornington Peninsula</h1>

      <div class="prose">
        <blockquote>
          <p><strong>TL;DR</strong></p>
          <ul>
            <li>The Peninsula works well for families but the best family activities are concentrated on the bay side and in specific hinterland attractions — not the ocean beach side.</li>
            <li><a href="/explore/arthurs-seat-lookout/">Arthurs Seat Eagle</a> is the single most consistently useful family attraction: short, visual, and manageable.</li>
            <li><a href="/explore/balnarring-beach/">Balnarring Beach</a> and <a href="/explore/safety-beach-foreshore/">Safety Beach</a> are the best bay beaches for children under 8.</li>
            <li>Ashcombe Maze is more engaging for children than its description suggests.</li>
          </ul>
        </blockquote>

        <p>The Mornington Peninsula, Victoria, Australia is a genuine family destination — but it works best with clear category thinking. The Peninsula's most celebrated experiences (hot springs, winery lunches, sunset walks) don't map well to children. What does map well: calm bay beaches, the gondola, the maze, specific wildlife, a handful of foreshore walks, and a market morning.</p>

        <h2>Beaches</h2>

        <h3>Best for young children (under 8)</h3>

        <p><a href="/explore/balnarring-beach/"><strong>Balnarring Beach</strong></a> — Shallow gradient, small waves, clear water, foreshore shading. The Peninsula's best toddler-friendly beach by a margin.</p>

        <p><a href="/explore/safety-beach-foreshore/"><strong>Safety Beach foreshore</strong></a> — Long and accessible, easy parking, calm water. Less character than Balnarring but consistently uncrowded.</p>

        <p><a href="/explore/mount-martha-beach/"><strong>Mount Martha Beach</strong></a> — Slightly more facilities nearby than Balnarring. Good for children 5+ who want a longer beach run.</p>

        <h3>What to avoid for young families</h3>
        <p>Ocean beaches (Sorrento Back Beach, Gunnamatta, Rye Ocean Beach). Rip activity and cold water make these unsuitable for swimming with children. Fine for a clifftop walk, not for beach play.</p>

        <h2>Attractions</h2>

        <p><a href="/explore/arthurs-seat-lookout/"><strong>Arthurs Seat Eagle</strong></a> — The gondola to the Arthurs Seat summit. 15 minutes each way. Manageable for all ages. The summit views are genuinely arresting — you see both the bay side and the ocean side simultaneously. The <a href="/journal/arthurs-seat-eagle-visitor-guide/">Arthurs Seat Eagle visitor guide</a> has timings and booking advice. Pairs naturally with <a href="/explore/dromana-beach/">Dromana Beach</a> nearby.</p>

        <p><strong>Ashcombe Maze and Lavender Gardens — Shoreham</strong> — More engaging than it sounds. The hedge maze holds genuine mystery for children. The lavender gardens give parents something. Recommend ages 5+; the maze is better for children who can navigate independently.</p>

        <h2>Walks</h2>

        <p><a href="/explore/cape-schanck-boardwalk/"><strong>Cape Schanck boardwalk</strong></a> — Short, flat, dramatic. Children understand what they're looking at immediately — the blowholes and sea platforms are engaging without narration. 30–40 minutes round trip.</p>

        <p><a href="/explore/mornington-foreshore-walk/"><strong>Mornington foreshore walk</strong></a> — Flat, accessible, with café stops. Good for families with prams.</p>

        <p><a href="/explore/summit-circuit-arthurs-seat/"><strong>Arthurs Seat summit circuit</strong></a> — The circuit from the gondola top station. Manageable for children 6+ with adult supervision.</p>

        <h2>Markets</h2>
        <p><a href="/explore/red-hill-market/">Red Hill Community Market</a> — First Saturdays. Food stalls, space to run. A reliable family morning anchor.</p>
        <p>Balnarring Farmers Market — Third Saturdays. Similar format, quieter.</p>

        <h2>Food</h2>
        <p>Family dining on the Peninsula is better than the national average. Most good cafés and mid-range restaurants accommodate children without drama. High chairs are standard in the better family-oriented areas (Mornington, Dromana, Safety Beach). Avoid expecting high-end winery restaurant dining to be child-friendly without checking first.</p>

        <h2>Further reading</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/journal/mornington-peninsula-with-kids/">Peninsula with kids — the full guide</a></li>
          <li><a href="/escape/the-family-day-out/">The family day out package</a></li>
          <li><a href="/explore/beaches/">The Peninsula's best beaches</a> — for beach-by-beach detail</li>
        </ul>

        <p><em>Last fact-verified 23 April 2026</em></p>

        <h2>FAQ</h2>

        <h3>What is the best beach on the Mornington Peninsula for families with young children?</h3>
        <p>Balnarring Beach — shallow, calm, clear water, easy parking. Safety Beach is a close second.</p>

        <h3>Is Peninsula Hot Springs suitable for children?</h3>
        <p>Peninsula Hot Springs has a children's bathing area, but the experience is primarily designed for adults. Ages 5+ can enjoy parts of it; under-5s are a judgment call.</p>

        <h3>What is the best paid attraction for families on the Mornington Peninsula?</h3>
        <p>Arthurs Seat Eagle gondola for children 2–12. Ashcombe Maze for children 5+.</p>

        <h3>What is the best season for a family Peninsula trip?</h3>
        <p>Summer for beaches. The school holidays (January, July) are crowded; October and early December have good weather with lower crowds.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <NewsletterBlock />
</BaseLayout>
